  "why": "The paper goes beyond merely reporting jailbreak successes: it analyzes where and how failures occur (per-model and per-behavior jailbreak rates, transferability across models, defended performance) and performs ablations that identify which attacker strategies (role-playing, logical appeal, chain-of-thought, in-context examples, attacker model choice, stream/depth tradeoffs) increase success. These analyses characterize statistical patterns of failures and link them to aspects of the attack design and model safety fine-tuning. However, the paper does not trace failures to deep underlying causes such as corrupted or biased training data, spurious features exploited by the model, or internal model activations — i.e., it does not provide diagnostic explanations that identify root causes at the model/data level. Therefore the paper provides partial diagnostic insight (pattern-level and ablation analyses) but not full causal root-cause diagnostics.",
